# Jump Game IX — Prefix/Suffix Observation

The standard Jump Game IX problem is usually solved using:

* Dynamic Programming
* Monotonic Stack
* Minimum Cost Transitions

We are given:

* `nums[]` → heights
* `cost[]` → jump cost

Goal:
Reach the last index with minimum total cost.

---

# Valid Jump Rules

A jump from `i` to `j` (`i < j`) is valid if:

## Valley Jump

```text id="mjlwmx"
nums[i] <= nums[j]
```

and all elements between them are smaller than `nums[i]`.

## Mountain Jump

```text id="20c3bh"
nums[i] > nums[j]
```

and all middle elements are greater than or equal to `nums[i]`.

---

# Standard DP Transition

```text id="0hdfiu"
dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[i] + cost[j])
```

The main objective is to generate valid next jumps efficiently and minimize total cost.

---

# My Prefix/Suffix Based Idea

Instead of DP + stacks, this approach uses global boundaries.

## Prefix Maximum

```text id="nnvk3j"
pref[i] = max(0...i)
```

Stores the maximum value seen so far.

## Suffix Minimum

```text id="q17s4u"
suf[i] = min(i...n-1)
```

Stores the minimum value ahead.

These arrays create a valid range/corridor for analysis.

---

# Greedy Backward Traversal

A pointer:

```text id="od4u0l"
far
```

tracks a smaller future candidate.

Core logic:

```java id="r5l6vh"
if(nums[far] < pref[i] && nums[far] >= suf[i])
    ans[i] = ans[far];
else
    ans[i] = pref[i];
```

Update:

```java id="dpxz5h"
if(nums[i] < nums[far])
    far = i;
```

---

# Important Observation

This solution does NOT solve the original Jump Game IX problem because:

* Standard problem requires DP optimization.
* It minimizes jump cost.
* My approach only performs:

  * prefix/suffix analysis
  * greedy inheritance
  * range propagation

So this behaves more like:

* a greedy range problem
* prefix/suffix boundary analysis

rather than shortest path dynamic programming.
